  "text": "## Graceful Shutdown Signal Handling Across Go Services\n\n### Kubernetes (kubernetes/kubernetes)\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\nKubernetes implements SIGTERM/SIGINT handling in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal.go`. The `SetupSignalContext()` function (line 40) creates a channel with buffering for 2 signals, calls `signal.Notify(shutdownHandler, shutdownSignals...)` (line 46), and returns a context that is cancelled on the first signal. Signals are defined in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/signal_posix.go` as `shutdownSignals = []os.Signal{os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM}` (line 26). On the second signal, the process exits with code 1 (line 51 in signal.go).\n\n**Shutdown Timeout & Cleanup Ordering:**\nKubernetes employs a sophisticated lifecycle signaling system in `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/lifecycle_signals.go` that defines multiple shutdown phases:\n- `ShutdownInitiated`: SIGTERM/SIGINT received\n- `AfterShutdownDelayDuration`: After 70 seconds (configurable)\n- `PreShutdownHooksStopped`: Pre-shutdown hooks completed\n- `NotAcceptingNewRequest`: Server stops accepting new requests\n- `InFlightRequestsDrained`: Existing requests completed (with 60s timeout)\n- `HTTPServerStoppedListening`: HTTP server stopped\n\nIn `staging/src/k8s.io/apiserver/pkg/server/genericapiserver.go` (lines 645-710), the graceful termination implements drain ordering:\n1. Pre-shutdown hooks run first (line 645-648)\n2. In-flight non-long-running requests drain with timeout enforcement (line 650-673)\n3. Active watch requests drain with rate limiting (line 675-706)\n4. Only after draining complete does it signal shutdown (line 708-710)\n\n### Prometheus (prometheus/prometheus)\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\nPrometheus handles SIGTERM/SIGINT in `cmd/prometheus/main.go` using the `oklog/run` package's Group pattern. Line 1154-1155 creates a signal channel: `term := make(chan os.Signal, 1)` and registers handlers with `signal.Notify(term, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)`. The termination handler is added as a run group at line 1157.\n\n**Shutdown Timeout & Cleanup Ordering:**\nPrometheus uses the run.Group pattern to establish cleanup ordering:\n1. Termination handler receives signal (line 1161-1162) and initiates graceful exit by logging and closing the reloadReady channel\n2. Signal closes cancel channel (line 1172)\n3. WebHandler is set to Stopping state (line 1173) to stop accepting new requests\n4. Then discovery managers stop (line 1187-1188)\n5. Rule manager stops (line 1216-1217)\n6. Scrape manager stops before closing storage to avoid writing to closed storage (line 1241) - demonstrating careful drain ordering\n7. Configuration reload handler stops (line 1341)\n\nThe run.Group pattern ensures sequential shutdown: when one goroutine exits, its corresponding cleanup function runs before the next begins.\n\n### Grafana (grafana/grafana)\n\n**Signal Handler Registration:**\nGrafana registers signal handlers in `pkg/cmd/grafana-server/commands/cli.go` in the `listenToSystemSignals()` function (line 148). Two separate channels are created:\n- `sighupChan` for SIGHUP (line 150, line 152)\n- `signalChan` for interrupt/SIGTERM (line 149, line 153)\n\nThe channel setup: `signal.Notify(signalChan, os.Interrupt, syscall.SIGTERM)` (line 153) and `signal.Notify(sighupChan, syscall.SIGHUP)` (line 152).\n\n**Shutdown Timeout & Cleanup Ordering:**\nGrafana implements a 30-second graceful shutdown timeout in `listenToSystemSignals()` (line 162): `ctx, cancel := context.WithTimeout(ctx, 30*time.Second)`. When SIGTERM/SIGINT is received (line 161), it calls `s.Shutdown(ctx, ...)` (line 164).\n\nThe Server.Shutdown() method in `pkg/server/server.go` (line 155):\n1. Uses sync.Once to ensure single execution (line 157)\n2. Shuts down all background services via `s.managerAdapter.Shutdown(ctx, \"shutdown\")` (line 159)\n3. Waits for shutdown with timeout enforcement using select on ctx.Done() (line 162-166)\n4. Returns timeout error if deadline exceeded (line 165)\n\nThe gRPC server shutdown in `pkg/services/grpcserver/service.go` (line 184-198) demonstrates drain ordering:\n1. Initiates graceful stop in a goroutine (line 188)\n2. Waits for completion or timeout (line 192-197)\n3. Forces Stop() if graceful shutdown times out (line 197)\n\nThe HTTP server in `pkg/api/http_server.go` (lines 508-510, 517-519) handles graceful shutdown by catching `http.ErrServerClosed` errors, indicating servers shut down gracefully.\n\n### Key Patterns Observed\n\n**Signal Registration Common Pattern:**\nAll three services register handlers with buffered channels (1-2 capacity) and signal.Notify() for SIGTERM and SIGINT (or os.Interrupt on Unix).\n\n**Shutdown Timeout Implementation:**\n- Kubernetes: Multiple configurable timeouts per phase (70s shutdown delay, 60s request timeout, configurable watch grace period)\n- Prometheus: Implicit timeout through run.Group exit coordination\n- Grafana: 30-second global timeout with per-service timeouts (10s for gRPC server)\n\n**Cleanup Ordering (Draining Before Stopping):**\n- Kubernetes: Pre-hooks → Non-long-running requests → Watch requests → Server close\n- Prometheus: Signal received → Stop accepting requests → Drain discovery managers → Drain rule manager → Drain scrape manager (before storage close) → Drain config reloaders\n- Grafana: Signal received → Shutdown background services → Wait with timeout → Force stop if needed\n\nAll three implementations ensure that existing work (in-flight requests, active watches, pending operations) is allowed to complete gracefully before stopping the underlying transport or storage systems, preventing data loss and connection errors."
